page.title: 01CRAIGENLEE FELL AND DUNSKEY
page.content: In this area of low rolling hills, agricultural grassland predominates, mostly intensively managed, but including much rough grazing and some moorland, the fields being enclosed usually by hedges or dry stone dykes. The south-western corner of the area differs from the remainder in consisting mainly of mature deciduous woodland with small strands of immature coniferous plantations and two small lochs, all of which form part of the Dunskey estate. The highest point of the area is Graigenlee Fell (180m) a watershed giving rise to several small burns.
